<div id="review_2133596227" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2133596227" />
    <a title="rosamund" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/51041100-rosamund"><img alt="rosamund" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1638874442p2/51041100.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2133596227?book_show_action=true">Sep 24, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="rosamund" class="user" itemprop="url" name="rosamund" href="/user/show/51041100-rosamund">rosamund</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/51041100-rosamund?shelf=ya">ya</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2133596227" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15474050181930393423">I picked this up in the Ufizzi in Florence, surely the most felicitous place to find this novel. I have admired many of Napoli&apos;s books, but this is one of my favourites. Napoli&apos;s evocation of 15th century Tuscany -- its excess, its art, its landscape, its beauty -- is wonderful. Her lush style suits her subjects, and it also gives the reader a vivid history of a tumultuous time in the history of Florence. Elisabetta is only 13 when the story begins, soon to be married off to secure her family&apos;s </span>
  <span id="freeText15474050181930393423" style="display:none">I picked this up in the Ufizzi in Florence, surely the most felicitous place to find this novel. I have admired many of Napoli's books, but this is one of my favourites. Napoli's evocation of 15th century Tuscany -- its excess, its art, its landscape, its beauty -- is wonderful. Her lush style suits her subjects, and it also gives the reader a vivid history of a tumultuous time in the history of Florence. Elisabetta is only 13 when the story begins, soon to be married off to secure her family's noble future. But tragedy strikes her protected world, and as always Napoli is an excellent writer of sadness and grief as well as beauty. This novel truly captures the bittersweet quality of life, of loss and wasted potential, and it's a compelling and moving story. </span>
  <a data-text-id="15474050181930393423" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


